  "answer": "The critic's objection misunderstands the role of the second forbidden case. The target does not require that a comprehensive ancient DNA survey already exists or is certain to be conducted; it identifies a type of evidence that, if obtained, would falsify the claim. Ancient DNA analysis of Late Bronze Age remains is a developing field, and pathogen DNA has been successfully recovered from archaeological samples of comparable or greater age (e.g., Yersinia pestis from Neolithic and Bronze Age contexts). The forbidden case is therefore a concrete, observable pattern that could realistically obtain as sampling and techniques advance—it is not an unfalsifiable shield. The standard does not demand that the disconfirming evidence already be in hand, only that it is in principle observable and would refute the mechanism if found. The target meets that requirement."
